<p>Does mewing work for adults? Short answer: not in the way most people hope — but that's not the whole story. The honest version is more nuanced, and understanding it will save you years of misplaced effort or, alternatively, make you stop dismissing something that could genuinely improve how you look.</p>

<p>Mewing — the practice of resting your tongue flat against the roof of your mouth — was popularised by Dr. Mike Mew of Orthotropics. The theory is that correct tongue posture applies upward and forward pressure on the maxilla and palate, influencing craniofacial development over time. In children, there's legitimate orthodontic and myofunctional backing for this. In adults, the picture changes significantly.</p>

<h2>Why Adults Are Different: The Bone Fusion Problem</h2>

<p>The core of the mewing debate in adults comes down to skeletal biology. The mid-palatal suture — the joint running down the middle of your palate — is the mechanism through which mewing is theorised to remodel the upper jaw. In children and adolescents, this suture is unfused and actively responsive to forces. Palatal expanders, which work on the same principle, are a standard orthodontic tool for kids precisely because this window of plasticity is real.</p>

<p>In adults, this suture typically fuses somewhere between the late teens and mid-twenties — though the timing varies significantly between individuals. Once fused, the forces generated by tongue posture alone are unlikely to produce measurable bone movement.</p>

<p>This is the honest ceiling for adult mewing results: <strong>significant skeletal remodelling, the kind you see in dramatic mewing before and after adults transformations online, is almost certainly not happening through tongue posture alone after the mid-palatal suture closes.</strong> Most of those dramatic adult transformations involve other factors — substantial weight loss, better posture, improved lighting and photography, or (sometimes unacknowledged) surgical intervention.</p>

<h2>What Mewing Can Actually Do for Adults</h2>

<p>Here's where the picture gets more useful. Even without skeletal remodelling, correct tongue posture produces several real, measurable effects in adults:</p>

<h3>1. Posture Correction</h3>
<p>Proper tongue posture is linked to better head-neck alignment. The tongue sitting in the roof of the mouth encourages the head to sit over the spine rather than jutting forward. Forward head posture is one of the most underappreciated factors in how your jaw and midface present — correcting it alone can produce visible changes in photos within weeks. This isn't mewing results in the dramatic structural sense, but it's real and it's fast.</p>

<h3>2. Nasal Breathing Shift</h3>
<p>You can't tongue-to-roof and mouth-breathe at the same time. Mewing, done correctly, enforces nasal breathing as your default. Nasal breathing has downstream effects: better sleep quality, lower cortisol, and reduced chronic facial puffiness from mouth breathing (which causes the upper lip to drop and the facial muscles to lose tone over time). This is likely responsible for much of the subtle improvement people notice in their faces over months of consistent mewing.</p>

<h3>3. Muscle Engagement and Facial Tone</h3>
<p>Holding proper tongue posture engages the muscles of the floor of the mouth and the neck musculature. Over time, this contributes to a more defined jaw-neck transition and reduces the flaccid appearance of the submental region. It's subtle — but it's not nothing.</p>

<h3>4. Long-Term Soft Tissue Effects</h3>
<p>Some researchers in the myofunctional therapy space argue that chronic muscle function patterns affect soft tissue position over years and decades — even in adults. The evidence here is weak and mostly observational, but it's the basis for why some adult mewing advocates report gradual improvements in midface appearance over multi-year timescales. This is plausible but not proven.</p>

<h2>What the Orthotropics Research Actually Says</h2>

<p>Dr. Mike Mew and the Orthotropics community have produced a body of case studies and observational work showing facial changes with myofunctional intervention. The problem is the evidence quality: these are case reports and small observational studies, not randomised controlled trials. Confounds are everywhere — age, weight change, photography angle, and selection bias (people who see results are more likely to post).</p>

<p>There are no high-quality RCTs specifically testing adult mewing outcomes for facial aesthetics. That's not unique to mewing — craniofacial research is difficult and expensive to run well — but it means the evidence base is substantially weaker than mewing advocates often imply.</p>

<p>What <em>is</em> well-supported: myofunctional therapy (of which correct tongue posture is a component) improves sleep-disordered breathing, reduces mouth breathing, and improves swallowing patterns in adults. The evidence for this is solid. The aesthetics claims are more speculative.</p>

<h2>The Honest Framework for Adults</h2>

<p>If you're an adult considering mewing, here's the framework that makes sense based on the evidence:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Expect posture improvements, not bone changes.</strong> Your jaw angle isn't going to shift. Your forward head posture improving over months? That's real, and it matters for how you look.</li>
  <li><strong>Expect nasal breathing benefits.</strong> If you're a chronic mouth breather, shifting to nasal breathing will improve sleep, reduce puffiness, and contribute to a more defined resting face over time.</li>
  <li><strong>Do not expect the dramatic mewing before and after adult results you see online.</strong> Apply basic critical thinking to transformation photos: what else changed? Body weight, lighting, age-related fat redistribution, photography angle. Most dramatic adult transformations have confounds.</li>
  <li><strong>Think in years, not weeks.</strong> Any legitimate soft tissue effect from correct tongue posture will manifest over 1–3+ years of consistent practice. If you're hoping for results in 90 days, you're setting yourself up for disappointment.</li>
  <li><strong>Stack it with other interventions.</strong> Body fat reduction, masseter development, chin tuck posture work, and face bloat reduction will all produce more visible improvement in less time than mewing alone. Mewing is a foundation practice, not a transformation tool.</li>
</ul>

<h2>How to Mew Correctly</h2>

<p>Most people who "try mewing" don't do it correctly, which is part of why results vary. The key errors:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Only the tongue tip touches the roof</strong> — incorrect. The <em>entire tongue</em>, including the back third, should be flat against the palate. The back of the tongue is the part that applies meaningful pressure to the posterior palate.</li>
  <li><strong>Jaw clenching</strong> — mewing does not mean clenching your teeth. Lips together, teeth lightly touching or slightly apart, tongue full contact on palate. Clenching all day leads to TMJ problems and masseter pain.</li>
  <li><strong>Forced swallowing</strong> — your swallow pattern should also change (mewing advocates a "suction swallow" that maintains palate contact). This takes time to habituate but matters for full myofunctional correction.</li>
</ul>

<p>The goal is to make correct tongue posture your default resting state — not something you consciously do for 10 minutes a day. It has to become automatic for any long-term effect to accumulate.</p>

<h2>Mewing vs. Actual Structural Interventions for Adults</h2>

<p>If you're an adult who genuinely wants structural facial improvement and you're being honest with yourself, here's the comparison:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>MARPE (Miniscrew-Assisted Rapid Palatal Expansion)</strong> — a surgical/orthodontic procedure that physically separates the mid-palatal suture in adults with hardware. This actually works for palatal expansion in adults. It's real medicine, invasive, expensive, and not for aesthetics-only use cases — but it demonstrates that palatal expansion in adults <em>is</em> possible with sufficient force.</li>
  <li><strong>Mewing</strong> — free, no risk (if done without clenching), genuine posture and nasal breathing benefits, minimal-to-zero structural bone effect after suture fusion.</li>
  <li><strong>Masseter training</strong> — mastic gum and jaw trainers produce real visible jaw widening over months. Faster and more predictable aesthetic ROI than mewing for most adults. See our <a href="/blog/skincare-looksmaxing/jawline-exercises-men">jawline exercises guide</a> for the full protocol.</li>
</ul>

<h2>The Bottom Line</h2>

<p>Mewing for adults is not the bone-remodelling tool it is for children and teenagers. The mid-palatal suture fusion issue is real, and the dramatic before/after transformations you see online almost always have confounding factors. An honest assessment of orthotropics mewing for adults is: strong evidence for posture and breathing benefits, weak evidence for structural remodelling.</p>

<p>That doesn't make it worthless. Correct tongue posture is how humans are supposed to rest. Making it habitual will improve your nasal breathing, head-neck alignment, and subtle facial muscle tone over time — all of which feed into how your face looks and how you carry yourself. It just won't reshape your maxilla.</p>

<p>If you're optimising your face as an adult, mewing is a low-cost background practice worth building in. But your bigger levers are body fat, bloating, masseter development, and posture correction through chin tucks. For the bloating side of the equation, see our <a href="/blog/skincare-looksmaxing/how-to-reduce-face-bloating-men">guide to reducing face bloating in men</a> — it's one of the fastest-visible improvements most guys can make.</p>

<p>One complementary practice worth pairing with mewing: <a href="/blog/biohacking-longevity/mouth-taping-sleep">mouth taping during sleep</a>. Since you can't maintain tongue posture consciously while asleep, taping enforces nasal breathing overnight — the same behaviour mewing promotes during waking hours. The combination reinforces the habit 24 hours a day.</p>

